  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering.  These efforts have significantly shaped national laws around the world. Here's a breakdown:\n\n**Key International Laws and Conventions:**\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the first major international agreements to address money laundering, though it primarily focused on drug-related proceeds.  It requires signatory nations to criminalize the laundering of money derived from drug trafficking and to cooperate in investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990 Strasbourg Convention):**  This convention expanded the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug-related crimes to encompass a wider range of predicate offenses (the underlying crimes that generate the illicit funds). It also established mechanisms for international cooperation in tracing, seizing, and confiscating illicit proceeds.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention further broadened the scope of money laundering offenses to include proceeds from any serious crime committed by an organized criminal group. It also emphasizes international cooperation in preventing and combating money laundering.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003 Merida Convention):** This convention focuses specifically on corruption-related money laundering. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds derived from corruption offenses and to strengthen international cooperation in combating corruption and recovering stolen assets.\n\n**The Financial Action Task Force (FATF):**\n\nWhile not a treaty or convention, the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** is an inter-governmental body that plays a crucial role in setting international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing.\n\n*   **FATF Recommendations:** The FATF develops and promotes policies and best practices for countries to implement. These recommendations cover a wide range of areas, including:\n    *   Criminalizing money laundering and terrorist financing\n    *   Customer due diligence (KYC) for financial institutions\n    *   Record-keeping requirements\n    *   Reporting suspicious transactions\n    *   International cooperation\n    *   Transparency of beneficial ownership\n\n    The FATF regularly assesses countries' compliance with its recommendations. Countries that are deemed non-compliant may face sanctions or other measures.  The FATF's influence is significant, and its recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n**Other Important Aspects:**\n\n*   **National Laws:**  The international conventions and FATF recommendations are typically implemented through national laws.  Most countries now have comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) laws that criminalize money laundering, require financial institutions to implement AML programs, and establish financial intelligence units (FIUs) to collect and analyze suspicious transaction reports.\n\n*   **International Cooperation:**  Combating money laundering effectively requires strong international cooperation.  This includes sharing information, providing mutual legal assistance, and extraditing offenders.\n\n**In summary:**\n\nYes, there are several key international laws and conventions against money laundering.  These, along with the FATF's influential recommendations, have established a global framework for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering.  These efforts are ongoing, as criminals constantly adapt their methods to evade detection.\n",
